bio:
Neil 'Stub Mandrel' Wyatt is an environmentalist ecologist and a lifelong model maker – he had his first workshop at the age of about fourteen. He cut his teeth on Airfix models, but branched out into model boats and aircraft (that flew about as well as the boats).

In his lathe thirties he discovered married life and a pile of ageing Model Engineer magazines and decided to take up the ‘ultimate hobby’ – making working things entirely from scratch – and bought a lathe. Whilst not claiming any exceptional talent, he gets great satisfaction from creating unusual working models and making and modifying tools and workshop equipment.

As well as model engineering his hobbies are electronics, microcontrollers, playing guitar and bass, astronomy and >gasp< 3D printing :-)

He somehow manages to combine being a environmental consultant with editing the magazine Model Engineers’ Workshop. Neil lives in Staffordshire with his wife, family and a collection of small to medium sized carnivorous mammals.

Visit www.stub.mandrel.co.uk for more thrills or www.nwenvironmental.consulting if you want me to help you save the planet!

The Swahili language defines Harambe as working together. Working together is exactly what we are wanting to accomplish. Our goal is to cooperate and communicate with our community. Every month we will upload a new design which people can access. Having access to the designs, people will be able to improve, customize, and personalize their own version. We all have different ideas and different ways of solving problems but here, we can take all methods and make them coexist. There are no limits and no useless comments. If you think that you can make it better, do it! Do not waste valuable time saying it. We are sharing our models for free. Please, do not sell our work. If you decide to use our design or create new components that are compatible, do not hesitate to mention us!

To the infinity and beyond!

bio: Physics teacher, moving into maker education.

My education is in electrical engineering and business management.

My career started as an electrical test engineer, designing and building test equipment and procedures for an industrial controls company.

Later I worked on mainframe ("super-mini) computers, which had a particular strength in high-speed networking. This lead into engineering (mechanical and electrical) software and applications used for various automotive, aerospace and consumer product's CAE/CAD/CAM (and product life-cycle management applications and data storage).

Currently I work as a software engineer in the financial analytics industry developing "cloud-based" software.

But the things I've most enjoyed to work on and create were the CAD software which had embedded within them specialized rules and algorithms my clients would specify. Learning of and optimizing a design process for a client was the most gratifying type of professional work I've done. The finished (software) product would allow the client to design a product quicker and to a higher degree of quality than they could before within their product domain. A competitive advantage.
